252
00:19:48,883 --> 00:19:50,014
Where's the dope?

253
00:19:50,145 --> 00:19:51,973
I thought you had it.

254
00:19:52,103 --> 00:19:53,496
Where's the dope?

255
00:19:53,627 --> 00:19:54,932
Brian, I'm scared.

256
00:19:55,063 --> 00:19:56,369
Hey, man,
what do you want?

257
00:19:56,499 --> 00:19:57,935
He's coming closer.

258
00:19:58,066 --> 00:19:59,372
Oh, my God.
He's got a gun.

259
00:19:59,502 --> 00:20:00,808
[gun fires]

260
00:20:00,938 --> 00:20:02,636
[groaning]

261
00:20:11,775 --> 00:20:12,776
[moaning]

262
00:20:23,744 --> 00:20:24,701
[man] Hmm.

263
00:20:31,926 --> 00:20:33,232
[gun firing]

264
00:20:57,604 --> 00:20:59,432
[chatter over police radio]

265
00:21:13,184 --> 00:21:14,751
[Lucca] <i>
"Dear Detective Lucca,</i>

266
00:21:14,882 --> 00:21:18,799
<i>this is the murderer</i><i>
of the two teenagers</i><i>
at the Simpson refinery</i>

267
00:21:18,929 --> 00:21:21,758
<i>and the two kids</i><i>
last Christmas</i><i>
at Red Rock Springs.</i>

268
00:21:21,889 --> 00:21:23,630
<i>I'm a little angry</i><i>
that you chose</i>

269
00:21:23,760 --> 00:21:25,893
<i>to ignore</i><i>
my last request.</i>

270
00:21:26,023 --> 00:21:28,591
<i>Perhaps now you'll print</i><i>
what I tell you to.</i>

271
00:21:28,722 --> 00:21:30,724
<i>To prove I killed them,</i><i>
I shall state some facts</i>

272
00:21:30,854 --> 00:21:32,682
<i>which only I</i><i>
and the police know.</i>

273
00:21:32,813 --> 00:21:35,772
One, brand name of ammo,
Super X.

274
00:21:35,903 --> 00:21:38,209
Two, nine shots were fired.

275
00:21:38,340 --> 00:21:40,037
Three, the boy
was on his back

276
00:21:40,168 --> 00:21:42,039
with his feet
to the car.

277
00:21:42,170 --> 00:21:44,520
Four, the girl
was on her right side

278
00:21:44,651 --> 00:21:46,566
with her feet
to the west.

279
00:21:46,696 --> 00:21:48,829
The girl was wearing
patterned slacks.

280
00:21:48,959 --> 00:21:51,788
The boy was also shot
in the knee. Western ammo.

281
00:21:51,919 --> 00:21:53,921
When I fired
the first shot
at his head,

282
00:21:54,051 --> 00:21:56,445
he leaped backwards
at the same time,

283
00:21:56,576 --> 00:21:58,186
thus spoiling my aim.

284
00:21:58,317 --> 00:22:00,101
He ended up
on the back seat,

285
00:22:00,231 --> 00:22:03,191
thrashing out
very violently
with his legs.

286
00:22:03,322 --> 00:22:05,541
That's how I shot him
in the knee.

287
00:22:05,672 --> 00:22:07,151
To assist you
in your investigation,

288
00:22:07,282 --> 00:22:10,024
I've enclosed
a composite drawing
of myself.

289
00:22:10,154 --> 00:22:12,505
If you don't
run this drawing
in tomorrow's paper,

290
00:22:12,635 --> 00:22:13,854
bad things will come.

291
00:22:13,984 --> 00:22:16,160
Me: four. You: zero."

292
00:22:16,291 --> 00:22:18,380
[Fredricks]
The guy's keeping score,
for Christ sakes.

293
00:22:18,511 --> 00:22:20,513
A third of the guys
on the force
look like this.

294
00:22:20,643 --> 00:22:22,123
Don't dismiss the fact

295
00:22:22,253 --> 00:22:23,994
that this guy
could be such
an egotistical maniac

296
00:22:24,125 --> 00:22:25,822
that he'd send us
an accurate drawing
of himself.

297
00:22:25,953 --> 00:22:27,650
[Brownlee] Why's
he writing to you, Jon?

298
00:22:27,781 --> 00:22:29,783
Who's he going
to write to,
Steve McQueen?

299
00:22:31,132 --> 00:22:32,176
He wants me involved.

300
00:22:32,307 --> 00:22:33,961
[Payne] Okay, okay.

301
00:22:34,091 --> 00:22:35,528
Aside from
his artistic skills,

302
00:22:35,658 --> 00:22:36,616
what else do we
know about him?

303
00:22:36,746 --> 00:22:38,748
A lot.

304
00:22:38,879 --> 00:22:42,665
He kills on weekends
around bodies of water,
lovers' lanes.

305
00:22:42,796 --> 00:22:44,493
No robberies,
no sex.

306
00:22:44,624 --> 00:22:46,974
He's one hell of a shot.

307
00:22:47,104 --> 00:22:49,585
[Payne] We're going to have
to release the letter.

308
00:22:49,716 --> 00:22:52,283
You guys better get ready
for a nightmare.

309
00:22:52,414 --> 00:22:54,111
[newsreader] <i>Homicide police</i><i>
would make no further comment</i>

310
00:22:54,242 --> 00:22:56,766
<i>after releasing the sketch.</i>

311
00:22:56,897 --> 00:22:58,246
<i>Detective Lucca</i><i>
is a highly decorated</i><i>
police officer.</i>

312
00:22:58,377 --> 00:22:59,900
[both] Mommy,
Daddy's on TV.

313
00:23:00,030 --> 00:23:01,249
Is he?

314
00:23:01,380 --> 00:23:03,730
Just a sec.
I'll come see.

315
00:23:03,860 --> 00:23:05,035
Huh? What have
we got here?

316
00:23:05,166 --> 00:23:07,386
Oh! It looks like...
What are you guys
playing?

317
00:23:07,516 --> 00:23:09,083
We're just
rolling these
down there.

318
00:23:09,213 --> 00:23:11,085
[Ann] Well, you know...

319
00:23:11,215 --> 00:23:13,740
We've got
the real thing.

320
00:23:13,870 --> 00:23:15,306
[Ann's father] It must
give you the creeps, huh, Jon?

321
00:23:15,437 --> 00:23:17,004
Having that guy
writing to you?

322
00:23:17,134 --> 00:23:18,701
[Ann] Guys threaten Jon
all the time.

323
00:23:18,832 --> 00:23:20,094
Honey, dinner.

324
00:23:20,224 --> 00:23:21,922
We get a dozen
Christmas cards

325
00:23:22,052 --> 00:23:23,837
from San Quentin
every year.

326
00:23:23,967 --> 00:23:26,100
We even got one
from the guy who
shot Jon last year.

327
00:23:26,230 --> 00:23:27,797
-Hmm.
-That was fun.

328
00:23:27,928 --> 00:23:29,016
People don't want
to go out at night.

329
00:23:29,146 --> 00:23:30,931
Business at the store
is down 70%.

330
00:23:31,061 --> 00:23:32,933
-Here, dear.
-Thank you.

331
00:23:33,063 --> 00:23:35,239
-More candles, hmm?
-Look, can we just please
stop talking about this?

332
00:23:35,370 --> 00:23:36,937
I'm not going
to say it again.

333
00:23:37,067 --> 00:23:38,678
That sauce needs
more red wine.

334
00:23:38,808 --> 00:23:40,854
I don't know.
This feels different,
and I don't know why.

335
00:23:43,073 --> 00:23:45,728
[Ann] Look, I don't want
to talk about this
anymore.

336
00:23:45,859 --> 00:23:48,514
I want us to have
a very nice
family dinner.

337
00:23:48,644 --> 00:23:49,776
Promise?

338
00:23:52,909 --> 00:23:55,434
That's when he started
writing to me directly.

339
00:23:57,174 --> 00:23:59,176
I remember.

340
00:23:59,307 --> 00:24:00,917
You couldn't
pick up a paper

341
00:24:01,048 --> 00:24:02,832
or put on the TV
without seeing you.

342
00:24:03,833 --> 00:24:05,139
Everybody knew
who you were.

343
00:24:06,314 --> 00:24:07,576
He made you
a celebrity.

344
00:24:11,885 --> 00:24:13,103
I was just doing my job.

345
00:24:16,585 --> 00:24:18,848
Everybody was waiting
for you to catch him.

346
00:24:23,200 --> 00:24:25,464
It must've been
very frustrating.

347
00:24:29,424 --> 00:24:30,730
[Brownlee] Man, ever since
you talked the Chief

348
00:24:30,860 --> 00:24:32,253
into running
that damn drawing,

349
00:24:32,383 --> 00:24:33,776
we've had calls
from everybody
and their uncle,

350
00:24:33,907 --> 00:24:37,084
saying the Scorekeeper's
their mailman
or their neighbor.

351
00:24:37,214 --> 00:24:38,651
[chuckles]
Or even their husbands!

352
00:24:40,304 --> 00:24:42,263
I mean, we've had 200,
300 husbands so far.

353
00:24:43,220 --> 00:24:44,874
Yeah, but no mothers.

354
00:24:48,399 --> 00:24:49,923
I'll bet you 10 bucks
this broad says her kid

355
00:24:50,053 --> 00:24:51,925
looks just like
Scorekeeper.

356
00:24:52,055 --> 00:24:53,753
He was the first
serial killer.

357
00:24:53,883 --> 00:24:55,363
Before him, there
was no such thing.

358
00:24:55,494 --> 00:24:58,061
There wasn't
even a label.

359
00:24:58,192 --> 00:24:59,759
We had no idea
what we were
dealing with.

360
00:25:00,803 --> 00:25:02,152
That's right.

361
00:25:04,503 --> 00:25:07,375
Serial killers are
a dime a dozen
nowadays, huh?

362
00:25:07,506 --> 00:25:10,160
Bundy, Gacy,
Kemper, Ramirez...

363
00:25:10,291 --> 00:25:12,075
Not to mention Dahmer.

364
00:25:13,163 --> 00:25:15,862
Seems like they come
in bunches, huh?

365
00:25:15,992 --> 00:25:17,254
Yeah, if you can
get a book deal

366
00:25:17,385 --> 00:25:20,083
or a motion picture
made out of it...

367
00:25:20,214 --> 00:25:23,478
You get your picture
on the cover of <i>Time.</i>

368
00:25:23,609 --> 00:25:27,961
Really. They always
make these guys out
to be such geniuses.

369
00:25:28,091 --> 00:25:32,574
David Berkowitz,
Son of Sam, remember?
[chuckles]

370
00:25:33,357 --> 00:25:35,534
Some criminal mastermind.

371
00:25:35,664 --> 00:25:37,013
He got caught
'cause he parked
in a red zone

372
00:25:37,144 --> 00:25:39,015
while he was
committing a murder.

373
00:25:39,146 --> 00:25:41,757
[chuckles]
They all get caught
in the long run.

374
00:25:43,977 --> 00:25:45,152
Sometimes
it takes a while,

375
00:25:45,282 --> 00:25:46,849
but it's not because
they're so smart.

376
00:25:46,980 --> 00:25:48,068
It's because the cops
are so stupid.

377
00:25:48,198 --> 00:25:49,765
[tires squealing]

378
00:25:58,557 --> 00:26:01,690
Pow.
Right between the eyes.

379
00:26:07,696 --> 00:26:10,220
But the young ones, oh,
they're the best to eat.

380
00:26:12,266 --> 00:26:14,398
Done much
hunting lately?

381
00:26:14,529 --> 00:26:16,662
No. My eyesight
isn't what it used to be.

382
00:26:20,317 --> 00:26:21,971
But I think about it
an awful lot.

383
00:26:25,671 --> 00:26:28,151
[woman] He says I made him
the way that he is.

384
00:26:28,282 --> 00:26:30,414
Can you believe that?

385
00:26:30,545 --> 00:26:33,026
You can't make somebody
the way that they are.

386
00:26:33,156 --> 00:26:35,202
They got to be
born that way.

387
00:26:35,332 --> 00:26:36,812
[Lucca] What kind of car
does he drive?

388
00:26:36,943 --> 00:26:38,031
He's got
a bunch of them.

389
00:26:38,161 --> 00:26:39,772
I can't
tell them apart.

390
00:26:39,902 --> 00:26:41,034
He keeps them
up at his trailer.

391
00:26:45,516 --> 00:26:46,735
[Brownlee] What are these for?

392
00:26:46,866 --> 00:26:47,823
Depression.

393
00:26:47,954 --> 00:26:50,565
But he'd never take them.

394
00:26:50,696 --> 00:26:52,436
Well, let's see,
Mr. Warden was arrested

395
00:26:52,567 --> 00:26:54,134
because he was
following around
some cheerleader,

396
00:26:54,264 --> 00:26:55,526
really harassing her.

397
00:26:55,657 --> 00:26:56,963
So her boyfriend
and a couple
of his buddies

398
00:26:57,093 --> 00:26:58,529
confronted him
after school,

399
00:26:58,660 --> 00:27:00,357
and he put them
in the hospital.

400
00:27:00,488 --> 00:27:01,837
The judge sees
no previous offenses,

401
00:27:01,968 --> 00:27:03,230
so he pops him
on probation

402
00:27:03,360 --> 00:27:05,624
and court-appointed
counseling.

403
00:27:05,754 --> 00:27:08,061
[Lucca] That sounds
pretty smart to me.

404
00:27:08,191 --> 00:27:10,933
Ah, he's very intelligent
in a basic sort of way.

405
00:27:11,064 --> 00:27:13,109
I think he might be
a developing sociopath.

406
00:27:19,376 --> 00:27:21,814
[woman] You know, you can
never let him know
that I called you.

407
00:27:24,033 --> 00:27:25,948
He talks about
those murders
all the time.

408
00:27:26,079 --> 00:27:28,995
He's... He's obsessed
with them.

409
00:27:29,125 --> 00:27:31,127
[Brownlee]
That doesn't really mean
anything, ma'am.

410
00:27:31,258 --> 00:27:34,087
And he looks
just like that drawing.

411
00:27:34,217 --> 00:27:37,656
Ah, it's quite rare
to encounter
the genuine article.

412
00:27:37,786 --> 00:27:41,137
The complete lack
of any real human emotion.

413
00:27:41,268 --> 00:27:45,794
Nothing but a series of
what we like to call
masks of normalcy.

414
00:27:45,925 --> 00:27:49,885
There's a theory developing
that sociopathic behavior
is controlled

415
00:27:50,016 --> 00:27:51,844
by a specific section
of the brain.

416
00:27:51,974 --> 00:27:53,106
It's called
the limbic region.

417
00:27:54,542 --> 00:27:55,935
It's the primitive part
of the brain

418
00:27:56,065 --> 00:27:57,414
that generates
and controls

419
00:27:57,545 --> 00:28:00,679
what we like to call
human emotion.

420
00:28:00,809 --> 00:28:02,942
Do you mind
if we keep
looking around?

421
00:28:03,072 --> 00:28:05,509
Look, I don't care
what you do. Okay?

422
00:28:05,640 --> 00:28:07,033
He's your problem now.

423
00:28:09,426 --> 00:28:12,125
Is he capable of murder?

424
00:28:12,255 --> 00:28:14,301
I don't know
what he's capable of.

425
00:28:31,405 --> 00:28:32,711
Man, open
a goddamn window.

426
00:28:34,103 --> 00:28:35,844
Smells like
something died
in there.

427
00:28:38,847 --> 00:28:40,196
[Lucca]
You take the inside,
I'll take the out.

428
00:28:40,327 --> 00:28:41,371
Thanks.

429
00:28:49,989 --> 00:28:51,773
I wish I had some gloves.

430
00:29:09,008 --> 00:29:09,835
[Brownlee] Hey, Jon...

431
00:29:13,708 --> 00:29:14,883
[Lucca] What a diet.

432
00:29:48,525 --> 00:29:49,918
Excuse me, what's
going on here?

433
00:29:50,049 --> 00:29:51,441
I'm Detective Lucca.

434
00:29:53,530 --> 00:29:55,271
I know who you are.

435
00:29:55,402 --> 00:29:57,099
I saw you on the news.

436
00:29:59,145 --> 00:30:00,407
I have
a search warrant here

437
00:30:00,537 --> 00:30:02,975
for your trailer,
your vehicle,
and your person.

438
00:30:03,540 --> 00:30:04,628
Why?

439
00:30:04,759 --> 00:30:06,326
We're investigating
a murder.

440
00:30:07,675 --> 00:30:08,937
Murder?

441
00:30:10,765 --> 00:30:12,332
Okay, go ahead.

442
00:30:12,462 --> 00:30:13,812
I'll check the car.

443
00:30:17,119 --> 00:30:18,425
I've written
this sentence.

444
00:30:20,731 --> 00:30:22,124
Rewrite it, please.

445
00:30:22,255 --> 00:30:24,170
Five times quickly.

446
00:30:24,300 --> 00:30:25,388
One after another,
please.

447
00:30:25,519 --> 00:30:27,477
Five times? Why?

448
00:30:27,608 --> 00:30:29,305
Do the best you can.

449
00:30:36,747 --> 00:30:39,315
You think I'm the guy
that killed those kids?

450
00:30:39,446 --> 00:30:40,969
If you don't mind.

451
00:30:46,148 --> 00:30:47,846
I can't believe this.

452
00:30:54,156 --> 00:30:55,418
I don't think
I can do it.

453
00:30:55,549 --> 00:30:57,507
I thought
you caught that guy.

454
00:30:57,638 --> 00:31:01,642
If you're not involved,
this'll prove it.

455
00:31:01,772 --> 00:31:03,122
You can go.

456
00:31:09,998 --> 00:31:12,653
What's with the dead animals
in the refrigerator?

457
00:31:12,783 --> 00:31:14,698
Oh, I'm working
on a degree.

458
00:31:14,829 --> 00:31:17,005
They're part of
my scientific research.

459
00:31:19,660 --> 00:31:21,401
I have a permit
for that.

460
00:31:22,532 --> 00:31:24,143
[Lucca] You like to hunt?

461
00:31:24,273 --> 00:31:25,231
Sometimes.

462
00:31:25,361 --> 00:31:26,493
Just a hobby.

463
00:31:26,623 --> 00:31:28,103
What do you hunt?

464
00:31:28,234 --> 00:31:31,498
[sighs] Depends.
Uh, raccoons, deer...

465
00:31:32,847 --> 00:31:34,153
Whatever's in season.

466
00:31:35,545 --> 00:31:37,721
Have you done
any hunting lately?

467
00:31:37,852 --> 00:31:39,201
No. I've been
studying for finals.

468
00:31:43,684 --> 00:31:46,469
Thank you.

469
00:31:46,600 --> 00:31:48,471
[Brownlee]
Do you mind taking
a ride with us, Mr. Warden?

470
00:31:48,602 --> 00:31:50,212
Wait a minute!

471
00:31:50,343 --> 00:31:52,519
I thought all I had
to do was write
what you asked me.

472
00:31:52,649 --> 00:31:54,782
Hey, Lloyd.
What the hell...

473
00:31:54,913 --> 00:31:59,221
I can't have cops
coming in here.
It don't look good.

474
00:31:59,352 --> 00:32:01,136
She said you scared
the shit out of her.

475
00:32:01,267 --> 00:32:02,703
She didn't give me
the details.

476
00:32:02,833 --> 00:32:04,531
She was too afraid to.

477
00:32:04,661 --> 00:32:06,576
Look, my mom's
afraid of the milkman.

478
00:32:13,714 --> 00:32:16,804
She said you were sick,
that I should watch you.

479
00:32:16,935 --> 00:32:18,632
She wouldn't
say that about me.

480
00:32:18,762 --> 00:32:20,242
She loves me,
and I love her.

481
00:32:20,373 --> 00:32:21,548
That's exactly
what she said to me.

482
00:32:23,767 --> 00:32:27,249
Now, why would
your mother tell me
something like that?

483
00:32:38,217 --> 00:32:39,435
Because she...

484
00:32:41,742 --> 00:32:43,439
Because she's sick.

485
00:32:44,397 --> 00:32:45,354
You met her.

486
00:32:46,921 --> 00:32:48,357
That's why
I live with her.

487
00:32:48,488 --> 00:32:50,098
Because I have
to take care of her.

488
00:32:57,584 --> 00:32:59,586
How about the incident
with the cheerleader?

489
00:33:02,893 --> 00:33:05,461
That was self-defense.

490
00:33:05,592 --> 00:33:07,333
The girl smiles at me,
and the next thing I know

491
00:33:07,463 --> 00:33:09,988
her boyfriends are ganging up
on me with baseball bats.

492
00:33:12,599 --> 00:33:14,296
Where'd you get those?

493
00:33:14,427 --> 00:33:16,429
Your mother.

494
00:33:16,559 --> 00:33:19,301
She says you're obsessed
with the murders.

495
00:33:19,432 --> 00:33:22,304
I'm not obsessed,
I'm just interested,
that's all.

496
00:33:22,435 --> 00:33:23,479
A lot of people are.

497
00:33:24,567 --> 00:33:26,352
I know the strain
that you're under,

498
00:33:26,482 --> 00:33:28,180
with everybody depending
